	abstract = {Impulsivity is a common complaint for adults, and it is a symptom of several mental health disorders. Research shows biofeedback interventions are efficacious in improving awareness and perceived control over internal states, potentially translating to better impulse control. Much of the research on biofeedback interventions for impulsivity, however, focuses on children and adolescents with attentional disorders. This pilot study evaluated the efficacy of biofeedback for improving self-regulation related to impulsivity in adults without a specific diagnosis. Undergraduate volunteers (n = 30) with reported impulsivity were randomly assigned to receive 3 sessions of either cognitive–behavioral (CB) intervention plus biofeedback training, or the CB intervention alone. The CB intervention consisted of exposure to stressful stimuli, guided relaxation training, and mindfulness. Results indicated that biofeedback training did not improve the efficacy of the CB intervention, but that self-reported impulse control improved from pre- to posttreatment for both treatment conditions. Future directions include research with larger samples, comparisons to waitlist control or more distinct interventions, and the evaluation of different biofeedback protocols for the treatment of adults with impulse control deficits. The development and dissemination of CB interventions that address impulse control deficits transdiagnostically has the potential to improve treatment outcomes for populations struggling with a wide range of disorders. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2024 APA, all rights reserved)},
