@incollection{black_westernmost_2024,
	title = {Westernmost: {Remoteness} and {Proximity} in {South} {Australia}},
	isbn = {978-1-040-08607-0},
	shorttitle = {Westernmost},
	abstract = {As part of an experimental research project led by Jana Norman and Emily Potter of Deakin University, Shadow Places, 1 inspired by work of Val Plumwood, we travelled 780 kilometres from Adelaide to the far west of South Australia, to Ceduna (pop. 3651), Penong (pop. 280) and Cactus Beach (no permanent population). Spending a few days there in early July 2023, with academics experimenting with creative modes of delivery, the aim was to create a link between these remote places and the metropolis, to find ways to think and feel differently about places that are ‘the underside of the capitalist fantasy, “the multiple disregarded places of economic and ecological support”' (Plumwood 2008, p. 139). These places, far from view and mind and sometimes out of sight but up close, are what, [Plumwood] says, we need to face and own, recognise and remember. These places are not outside ourselves, but implicated in the very constitution of our embodied, habitual and social lives. We differentially benefit from these places. (Potter et al. 2022, p. 286) The urgency of climate change and environmental issues has prompted the academics cited here to adopt a manifesto mode of delivery and to network more actively with community members in these shadow places. It is necessarily a collective kind of activity, aiming for sustainable connections rather than individual productivity. In the spirit of this collective production, two of us opted for a dialogic mode of inquiry: Prudence Since the late 1970s, Cactus has had a shadowy existence for me. I always knew about Cactus, even though I wasn’t a surfer. Stories coming back from people who had been there installed the place in my imagination in ways that people talk of as ‘legendary’. Looking at this photograph now (Figure 15.1) of this old surfers’ shack in Cactus materialises my imagination. There they are in close proximity to each other, and they are very close to the sea. They were a long way from Adelaide. Stephen Along with the ‘outback’ the beach is the most mythologised and romanticised space in Australian culture. 2 But are these two enjoying the remoteness and the proximity? What do these terms signify? Prudence It must be relative; Cactus is not remote if you feel you are present there. For the WiraŊu people, it always was, always is, home. Stephen That designation ‘remote’ is a way of asserting the metropolitan right to erase a place. The remote area is exploitable because nobody is supposed to be home. It is a shadow existence; not really real. Prudence Actually, proximity, it seems to me, is more important than difference. If you are close by to someone or something, why would you stress your difference from them, and thus feed the identity politics machine? Stephen Why indeed? Negotiating coexistence makes much more sense. With dolphins, for instance. Prudence With Coffin Bay oysters. Stephen With the north wind from the desert. Prudence With the reliable left-hand break. Stephen Nothing to do with difference; it’s all about being attached to such things. What you need to have rather than what you think you must be. Prudence All we need is an old Cactus shack. Stephen Now you are being nostalgic for something you never had. Nostalgia without an object. Prudence Actually, I preferred the campervan we travelled in, speaking of close proximity. I liked the way our bodies had to navigate the space - shifting, sliding, nudging and weaving. Let’s spin this out a bit. Can proximity be a kind of method in Cultural Studies? Stephen I think so. Difference was an orthodox theoretical concept from the 1980s (let me cite something from the website for the journal differences: ‘differences: A Journal of Feminist Cultural Studies first appeared in 1989 at the moment of a critical encounter - a head-on collision, one might say - of theories of difference (primarily Continental) and the politics of diversity (primarily American)'). Derrida’s influential différance meets US identity politics. Maybe it has run its course? Prudence The world has shrunk since then. ‘Interconnectedness’ and ‘entanglement’ are new catchphrases that are trying to grasp the vision of life on Earth where things depend on each other and are therefore more intimate with each other. It did feel intimate in the campervan. Stephen And that points to a new kind of reasoning. The old ethic, the Eurocentric one, was an expansive application of reason, Immanuel Kant’s sapere aude: ‘Dare to use your own understanding’. Isabelle Stengers glossed this: ‘[it] commits the children of the Enlightenment to behave as active subjects, wielding the weapon of reason’ (qtd in Pignarre 2023, pp. 142-143). She goes on to point out that sapere means ‘taste’ as well as ‘know’ (as in ‘savor’ and ‘savvy’). Sapere aude: ‘Dare to taste’. So the new kind of reasoning will be forged more by a slogan like, ‘Dare to let yourself be touched’ or ‘Dare to begin to understand otherwise’. Prudence Wait a minute. What on earth do you mean? That individual human reason is no longer the weapon of choice? I guess we are now thinking through more complex, affective, networks of relations with things. And non-humans have intelligence as well. But how does that help us do cultural studies in a place like Ceduna or Cactus? A cultural studies of proximity? Do we start by saying Ceduna and Cactus aren’t remote from us, in Adelaide? But hang on …. wasn’t that the draw of Cactus? That it was so far away? And isn’t it the distance that protects it from hordes of tourists? And isn’t it precisely because the instantaneous internet connections of social media bring it closer, that the managers of the Cactus campground have requested that people don’t post anything on Instagram? Stephen I think that is the dynamic we are exploring for possible analysis. If distance has been ingrained into Australian mythologies, we want to add proximity. Designations of ‘remote’ or ‘tyranny of distance’ cast places into shadows: too far away to matter, really. But once you start detailing the connections, things come suddenly closer. For instance, all the agricultural and mineral wealth pouring in from the Eyre Peninsula … that special short stalk species of wheat that is more suited to the dry conditions. Prudence Speaking of industry, that brings up two matters of concern we can conclude with. Remember Trina telling us the story of how she dressed in a seagull costume and walked to the Great Australian Bight to protest BPs plan to build off-shore fossil fuel extraction platforms? She has been living near Cactus for years, in a house that is ‘off the grid’. It was her backyard they threatened to spoil. Proximity made it really matter for her. Stephen I know. The other story we heard all about was the nuclear waste disposal idea for Kimba, some 300 kilometres away. The fight went on for years. It is so easy for people in the cities to be NIMBY. ‘Oh, no. Nuclear waste is far too dangerous to be buried anywhere near North Adelaide!' For the Kimba people, Kimba still wasn’t remote enough from the danger. The colonial idea of exporting your problems to someone else’s somewhere, while simultaneously importing the wealth gained from their lands … Prudence … hinges around designating them as remote. Stephen Whereas the very practice of bringing people into the conversation, like Sandy in Ceduna, who introduced us to Trina and others whose stories we heard, is all about understanding, negotiation, friendship, community and intimacy … I think our dialogue enacted that, at least a bit. It remains to conclude with a number of manifesto-like rhetorical ‘moves’ that feed into the transformations of the field of cultural studies as it struggles to think and feel about environmental crises: Move one: Stop using the adjective ‘remote’. Aboriginal groups like the WiraŊu, who have been at home there ‘since day one’ (as they like to put it), do not see themselves as ‘remote’ at all, while no doubt recognising the hegemonic view that services are delivered, and power and control exercised, by capital cities far to the east. But evocations of the ‘primitive’ have been traditionally been used as an economic strategy to hollow out a space for further exploitation. Such ‘representational rhetorics’ maintain a paradigm of oppositions: remote/settled, primitive/civilised, ancient/modern (West 2016). They work in parallel with, and facilitate, extraction industries because ‘remote’ is not only implies affective distance - it doesn’t matter to ‘us’ because it is too far away - but also that there is no one really at home. A rejection of remoteness returns us to considerations of the proximate. Move two: Ask what you are living off. Flying unnecessary stuff around the planet is a global logistical crisis. Kenneth Pomeranz called the mechanism for imperial wealth accumulation ‘ghost acreage’: in little Britain, the territory they lived on was not the territory they lived off (Latour \& Weibel 2020, p.15). Still today. You can live on a yacht in the Mediterranean if you can live off your shares in BHP, which was seeking to extract gas from the Great Australian Bight, near Ceduna. It is easy to moralise about living according to what one’s proximate territory can sustain. But how can one wind back economics of globalisation, so that it become more like an economics of what Bruno Latour calls ‘critical zones’? Move three (a militant move): In order to be absolutely clear, we put this in vernacular language: Don’t let them get away with it. Because the modus vivendi of the neo-liberal order is ‘whatever we can get away with’. But away to where? Stash the cash in an off-shore account? Proximity might imply a restraint on the freedoms associated with accumulation. We have to find a way to trick them into thinking there are all kinds of advantages, some of them economic, associated with proximity. But ‘they’, those leading the world with their immense wealth, are under the spell of a story, a techno-futurist colonisation story; they think it makes sense to fly off to Mars. Move four: Recraft the story, in order to recompose the commons. Russell West-Pavlov writes in the Introduction to this volume of a ‘matrix for potential co-existences’. And Vinciane Despret came up with a writing method, which can certainly contribute to ‘proximity-as-method’. As she embarks on an investigation into accounts of posthumous existences, someone tells her a story, and she writes: What do I do with this? What meanings are soliciting me? What kind of becoming can I offer this? It is a matter not of explaining but of understanding in the literal sense [com-prendre = ‘to take with’]. Allowing oneself to be instructed. Making a narrative matrix out of a story. It is a machine for making stories that go step by step; a matrix of stories that are constructed out of the preceding ones, and, as they do this, the one connects with the other, not on a thread, but in the way that a web is made. This is what we might call writing in three dimensions. Any point of the frame can give birth to a new narrative direction. (Despret 2021, p. 17) This ‘matrix for potential co-existences’ may not need a theory to explain or justify it. There are empirical connections ‘on the ground’, as it were. They are not simply existences, because they are also attachments. This is the starting point for our version of proximity-as-method. We suggest embarking on a description of what some entity has to have in order to persist, and that will mean describing it in all its heterogenous relationships. An ‘entity’ - a dolphin, a surfing break, a campervan, a human body - is already a bundle of relations, some proximate, some more remote. In the critical zones in which entities have evolved and in which they coexist with others, these relations shift and change, expand and contract, in ways we have yet to explore further. © 2024 selection and editorial matter, Riccarda Flemmer, Bani Gill, and Jacky Kosgei; individual chapters, the contributors.},
	language = {English},
	booktitle = {Proximity as {Method}: {Concepts} for {Coexistence} in the {Global} past and {Present}},
	publisher = {Taylor and Francis},
	author = {Black, Prudence and Muecke, Stephen},
	editor = {Flemmer, Riccarda and Gill, Bani and Kosgei, Jacky},
	year = {2024},
	doi = {10.4324/9781003495857-20},
	pages = {225--230},
}

@article{gangathimmaiah_what_2023,
	title = {What works for and what hinders deimplementation of low-value care in emergency medicine practice? {A} scoping review},
	volume = {13},
	issn = {2044-6055},
	shorttitle = {What works for and what hinders deimplementation of low-value care in emergency medicine practice?},
	doi = {10.1136/bmjopen-2023-072762},
	abstract = {Objectives Low-value care can harm patients and healthcare systems. Despite a decade of global endeavours, low value care has persisted. Identification of barriers and enablers is essential for effective deimplementation of low-value care. This scoping review is an evidence summary of barriers, enablers and features of effective interventions for deimplementation of low-value care in emergency medicine practice worldwide. Design A mixed-methods scoping review was conducted using the Arksey and O'Malley framework. Data sources Medline, CINAHL, Embase, EMCare, Scopus and grey literature were searched from inception to 5 December 2022. Eligibility criteria Primary studies which employed qualitative, quantitative or mixed-methods approaches to explore deimplementation of low-value care in an EM setting and reported barriers, enablers or interventions were included. Reviews, protocols, perspectives, comments, opinions, editorials, letters to editors, news articles, books, chapters, policies, guidelines and animal studies were excluded. No language limits were applied. Data extraction and synthesis Study selection, data collection and quality assessment were performed by two independent reviewers. Barriers, enablers and interventions were mapped to the domains of the Theoretical Domains Framework. The Mixed Methods Appraisal Tool was used for quality assessment. Results The search yielded 167 studies. A majority were quantitative studies (90\%, 150/167) that evaluated interventions (86\%, 143/167). Limited provider abilities, diagnostic uncertainty, lack of provider insight, time constraints, fear of litigation, and patient expectations were the key barriers. Enablers included leadership commitment, provider engagement, provider training, performance feedback to providers and shared decision-making with patients. Interventions included one or more of the following facets: education, stakeholder engagement, audit and feedback, clinical decision support, nudge, clinical champions and training. Multifaceted interventions were more likely to be effective than single-faceted interventions. Effectiveness of multifaceted interventions was influenced by fidelity of the intervention facets. Use of behavioural change theories such as the Theoretical Domains Framework in the published studies appeared to enhance the effectiveness of interventions to deimplement low-value care. Conclusion High-fidelity, multifaceted interventions that incorporated education, stakeholder engagement, audit/feedback and clinical decision support, were administered daily and lasted longer than 1 year were most effective in achieving deimplementation of low-value care in emergency departments. This review contributes the best available evidence to date, but further rigorous, theory-informed, qualitative and mixed-methods studies are needed to supplement the growing body of evidence to effectively deimplement low-value care in emergency medicine practice.  © Author(s) (or their employer(s)) 2023. Re-use permitted under CC BY-NC. No commercial re-use. See rights and permissions. Published by BMJ.},
	language = {English},
	number = {11},
	journal = {BMJ Open},
	author = {Gangathimmaiah, Vinay and Drever, Natalie and Evans, Rebecca and Moodley, Nishila and Sen Gupta, Tarun and Cardona, Magnolia and Carlisle, Karen},
	year = {2023},
	note = {Publisher: BMJ Publishing Group},
	keywords = {ACCIDENT \& EMERGENCY MEDICINE, ANTIBIOTIC USE, ANTIMICROBIAL STEWARDSHIP INTERVENTION, Change management, CLINICAL DECISION-SUPPORT, COMPUTED-TOMOGRAPHY UTILIZATION, HEALTH-CARE, LOW-BACK-PAIN, PULMONARY-EMBOLISM, Quality in health care, RANDOMIZED CONTROLLED-TRIAL, TRACT-INFECTION TREATMENT, URINARY CATHETER USE},
