	doi = {10.1063/5.0278362},
	abstract = {Artificial intelligence (AI) has revolutionized several domains, with language acquisition being one of its most significant areas of influence. The capacity of AI to customize learning, provide immediate feedback, and dismantle conventional obstacles to education has transformed language acquisition for global learners. AI-driven services like as Duolingo, Babbel, and Google Translate use techniques like Natural Language Processing (NLP), machine learning, voice recognition, and virtual instructors to provide dynamic, interactive, and immersive learning environments. These technologies allow learners to practice language skills at their own speed, get rapid feedback, and customize their learning trajectories according to their progress. The influence of AI is notably profound in enhancing the four essential language skills - reading, writing, speaking, and listening - by providing individualized and adaptive learning experiences that are sometimes absent in conventional classroom environments. Moreover, AI's function beyond the enhancement of language proficiency in predominant languages; it is also used to conserve and advocate for endangered languages, providing platforms for learners to interact with less typically taught languages such as Hawaiian and Navajo. AI-driven translation tools, such as Google Translate and Microsoft Translator, are enhancing cross-cultural communication and dismantling language obstacles, demonstrating their use in fields including international commerce, diplomacy, and tourism. Nonetheless, the rapid incorporation of AI in language acquisition presents obstacles. Challenges such excessive dependence on technology, the inadequacies of AI in conveying cultural subtleties, issues over data privacy, and the digital gap, especially in poor areas, need attention. Moreover, while AI may improve the technical aspects of language acquisition, it is inadequate in imparting the cultural context vital for genuine language proficiency. It is essential to balance AI use with human engagement while addressing ethical and accessibility issues to ensure that AI-driven language instruction is successful and fair. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
