	abstract = {Purpose: The aim of this study is to investigate how students’ social and educational norms and practices affect their attitudes and engagement towards improving English communication skills using a chatbot as a conversation partner. It examines the practices, views and challenges of students who are aiming to improve their spoken communication skills with the chatbot in the conventional language classroom. Method: Based on a small-scale study conducted at universities in Japan, this research employs both qualitative and quantitative questionnaire-based surveys to examine students’ attitudes and views on engaging in simulated real conversations using a chatbot for a period of eight weeks in an English language course. Particular attention was also paid to examining the differences between experienced and novice chatbot users’ first-hand experiences of speaking intervention tasks. Results: The findings revealed that students had positive views on the chatbot-facilitated intervention in the classroom, but they were shaped by the socio-educational norms and practices that they were accustomed to and their expectations informed by their prior experiences. Their views were also influenced by their previous utility of such AI technology. Conclusion: This study provides valuable insights into how to effectively utilise a chatbot as an educational tool to help students personalise language learning experiences in diverse social and educational contexts. Teachers need to be equipped with the knowledge that students’ socio-educational backgrounds and their language learning approaches are inseparable and indistinguishable. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
