	abstract = {This study investigated the potential of integrating artificial intelligence (AI) capabilities into Dynamic Assessment (DA) to enhance second language (L2) learning. It aims to shed light on using AI to teach pragmatics, address the scarcity of research in this area, and develop an AI learning platform to meet the need for effective online language tools. To this end, an online AI chatbot platform was developed to function as an instructor, offering Dynamic Assessments (DA). The research, using an Explanatory Mixed Method Design, examined different feedback types—Artificial Intelligence Interventionist Dynamic Assessment (AIIDA), Classroom Interventionist Dynamic Assessment (CIDA), and Direct Feedback (DF)—on immediate and delayed apology and request speech act learning. To accomplish this, 125 undergraduate university students from four intact classroom groups were assigned to the study, which employed a pre-test post-test design with simple random sampling. This number decreased to 87 due to subject mortality and statistical considerations. ANCOVA analysis findings indicate that no significant differences were observed between AI dynamic assessment and classroom dynamic assessment, or between AI dynamic assessment and direct feedback. In contrast, classroom dynamic showed a significant benefit comparing with direct feedback in improving both immediate (sig. = 0.016) and delayed (sig. = 0.041) speech act learning. To elucidate the results, a group interview was conducted to gather participants’ perspectives on the AI platform. The overall findings suggest that AI has the potential to serve as a support for teachers in second language learning by providing around-the-clock personalized feedback, automating tasks, and adaptive learning resources. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
