	abstract = {This study compared the role of ChatGPT4o as an AI assessor with that of human assessors (teachers and students) in Chinese college EFL speaking classrooms, focusing on the reliability in holistic and analytic scoring and the actionability of feedback for improvement. Twenty-six freshmen English majors completed recorded oral exams, which were scored both holistically and analytically (with time intervals) by ChatGPT4o and by human raters, including four experienced EFL teachers and 20 students from a parallel class. In addition, both AI and human assessors provided qualitative feedback on accuracy, fluency, and complexity domains of these oral exams. Follow-up interviews with teachers and selected student assessors explored their perceptions of ChatGPT4o as an AI assessor in classroom assessments. The results showed that ChatGPT4o provided more detailed feedback than human assessors across all domains. While the reliability coefficient values for ChatGPT4o’s scoring were slightly lower than those of teachers, they were significantly higher than those of student assessors. Interviews revealed mixed perspectives on adopting ChatGPT4o, with participants recognizing its comprehensive feedback capabilities but expressing concerns about its accessibility, cost, and limited contextual understanding. Implications for integrating AI in classroom assessments are discussed. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
