	doi = {10.1016/j.neucom.2025.130846},
	abstract = {Alzheimer's disease (AD) is a prevalent neurodegenerative disorder affecting the older adult population worldwide. Among the available cognitive screening methods, neuropsychological scale assessments (NSA) are widely employed in clinical practice to evaluate patients’ cognitive functions, particularly through speech-related tasks. However, manual evaluation of NSA is often labor-intensive and susceptible to subjective bias. While Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) technology offers the potential to automate this process, it frequently faces notable challenges in handling dialectal variations, unclear pronunciations, and insufficient annotated data. These factors often lead to inaccuracies in transcribed speech and hinder the effective validation of assessment outcomes. To address these challenges, particularly the data bottleneck, we propose a novel dual-use paradigm for Large Language Models (LLMs). In this study, we designed an innovative agent framework employing LLMs not only for automated NSA scoring, thereby replacing manual assessment, but also for reverse-engineering clinical data by simulating patients with varied cognitive impairments. These synthetically generated NSA texts are then utilized in a closed-loop learning process as a form of “supervised learning” to iteratively refine the system prompts of an NSA evaluation agent. The prompt design explicitly incorporates the dialectal speech and pronunciation ambiguities, aiming to equip the NSA evaluation agent with evaluation and reasoning proficiencies comparable to those of experienced clinicians. The evaluations on a dataset of real-world clinical cases demonstrated a substantial 86\% consistency between the NSA evaluation agent's assessments and those of expert physicians, indicating the potential of LLM-driven approaches for accurate and scalable automated NSA in AD screening and beyond. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
