	abstract = {Digital technology has had an unavoidable impact on business, which, in turn, has led to changes in social areas. For example, digital innovations in business can result in people being made redundant, i.e. losing their jobs. It is an inescapable fact that employment (or the lack of it) has huge effects on society. The big data of modern AI drives big changes, changes which can be frighteningly fast. We (the instigators of change) are not even always sure whether we made the decisions ourselves or whether we were nudged in a certain direction. The exigencies of the current global business environment have led to the implementation of a plethora of innovative AI applications for finance, behavioral biometrics and even Natural Language Understanding (NLU). These are powerful tools, but there has been no independent and coordinated assessment of the very real risks these AI technologies may precipitate, at least not in terms of specific working environments. All the aforementioned threats (and opportunities) are newcomers from the world of Artificial Intelligence (AI). Therefore, it is vital to review the role that AI plays in the life of any business enterprise. One problem is that many enterprises are early adopters of AI and thus may be over-reliant on artificial intelligence while not fully understanding the knock-on effects that it can have on a company's business model. In contrast to the early-adopters of AI, there are some businesses whose more conservative management style has not yet introduced the latest AI technologies into their business practices. Such businesses are waiting for the appropriate AI tools to be developed which would ensure their business a competitive advantage and thus justify their investment. Finally, there are many enterprises that have the capacity for AI implementation but cannot be sure whether the company will benefit from it, or whether AI technology might contain the seeds of the company's collapse. For such companies