	abstract = {This paper is a survey of results in the approximation theory ofanalytic functions with a view to proposing methods of numerical analytic continuation in various situations. It is easily readable,avoids becoming highly technical while preserving clarity of expositionand offers an opportunity to discuss various views on the problem ofanalytic extrapolation. Particularly, the author recommends use of the``AAA'' algorithm for generating rational approximants to continue dataavailable in the domain of analyticity. While one is reading the paper underreview, the book \{{\textbackslash}it Approximation theory and approximationpractice\} [extended edition [of [msn] 3012510 [/msn]], SIAM,Philadelphia,PA, 2020; [msn] MR4050406 [/msn]] by the author is an excellent companion.{\textbackslash}par Although this is not part of the present paper, a short description ofthe AAA method seems necessary. Values \$f\_i\$,\$i=1,{\textbackslash}dots,M\$, are available at points \$z\_i\$, \$i=1,{\textbackslash}dots, M\$; by choosing\$m\&lt;M\$pointsand values out of these, one looks for rational functions \$r(z)\$ oforder \$(m-1,m-1)\$ of the form:\$\$r(z)={\textbackslash}frac\{{\textbackslash}sum\_\{i=1\}{\textasciicircum}m{\textbackslash}frac\{w\_if\_i\}\{z-z\_i\}\}\{{\textbackslash}sum\_\{i=1\}{\textasciicircum}m{\textbackslash}frac\{w\_i\}\{z-z\_i\}\}{\textbackslash}equiv{\textbackslash}frac\{n(z)\}\{d(z)\}.\$\$These functions satisfy identically \$r(z\_i)=f\_i\$, independently of the choiceofthe weights \$w\_i\$. This degree of freedom is used to choose the valuesof the latter (their sum of squares is normalized to unity) so as tominimize the least squares difference \${\textbackslash}sum\_\{i=m+1\}{\textasciicircum}M {\textbar}f\_id(z\_i)-n(z\_i){\textbar}{\textasciicircum}2 \$ at the remaining \$M-m\$ pairs \$(z\_i,f\_i)\$. In [SIAM J.Sci. Comput. \{{\textbackslash}bf 40\} (2018), no.{\textasciitilde}3, A1494--A1522; [msn]MR3805855 [/msn]], Y. Nakatsukasa, O. Sète and the author of the currentpaper gave the linearalgebra equations determining the \$w\_i\$ andargued that the matrices whose inversion is required have a betterconditioning than those used in conventional rational function fitting.Computer codes producing these approximations were also offered [Y. Nakatsukasa, O. Sète and L.{\textasciitilde}N.Trefethen, op. cit.]. The name AAA means ``adaptive-Antoulas-Anderson'', inreference to a paper of A.{\textasciitilde}C. Antoulas and B.{\textasciitilde}D.{\textasciitilde}Q. (B.{\textasciitilde}D.{\textasciitilde}O.) Anderson [IMA J. Math. Control. Inform. \{{\textbackslash}bf 3\} (1986), no.{\textasciitilde}2-3, 61--88,{\textbackslash}doi\{10.1093/imamci/3.2-3.61\}]where a related algorithm wasproposed. It is essential that the poles of \$r(z)\$ are obtained fromthe zeros of \$d(z)\$ and thus are ``freely moving'', i.e., their positionis determined by the fitted data without any other restriction.{\textbackslash}par The paper under review starts with a discussion of the approximation byrationalfunctions of an analytic function \$f(z)\$ given on \$[-1,1]\$, placing itin contrast with the approximation by polynomials. For the latter, theposition of the ``closest'' singularity controls the possible rate ofconvergence of polynomials. If the smallest ellipse with foci at \$z={\textbackslash}pm1\$ and passing through the singularity has parameter (sum of thetwo half-axes) \${\textbackslash}rho\$, then there exist polynomials \$p\_n\$ approximating \$f\$on \$[-1,1]\$ like \$C{\textbackslash}rho{\textasciicircum}\{-n\}\$; these polynomials converge to \$f(z)\$uniformly on compact sets inside the ellipse at an exponential rate.{\textbackslash}par No such estimates are possible for rational approximants with``moving'' poles; in principle, they may do much better, and offerextrapolations on extended regions, as illustrated in the paper by theAAA algorithm applied on several examples, either from data on the\$[-1,1]\$ interval on functions with nearby singularities (e.g., \${\textbackslash}tanh z\$) orattempting a numerical reconstruction of the Riemann \${\textbackslash}zeta\$function, starting from values at points along a complex segment or thereconstruction of conformal mappings starting from the mapping functionof the boundary. Sometimes the results are so impressive that one istempted to believe that analytic continuation poses no seriousproblems.{\textbackslash}par Section 5 of the paper hurries to destroy such illusions---althoughthe author tries to find the bright side of the destruction. He givesexamples of functions---analytic in a sizable neighborhood of the realaxis---which on large intervals of the real axis vanish to a machineprecision of 16 digits and then ``recover'' on other intervals tobecome unity also to this precision. Clearly, ``blind'' analyticextrapolation from machine-generated data on a finite interval cannotexclude a{\textasciitilde}priori such functions. Manipulating them, the authorshows how to produce analytic (machine-)interpolants between disjointpieces of analytic functions or other constructions which areimpossible at zero errors.{\textbackslash}parSection 6 is the ``heart'' of the approximation part of the paper: itgives a resumé of results of J.{\textasciitilde}L. Walsh [\{{\textbackslash}it Interpolation andapproximation by rational functions in the complex domain\}, fourth edition,Amer. Math. Soc. Colloq. Publ., Vol. XX, Amer. Math. Soc., Providence, RI,1965 (Chapters VIII and IX); [msn] MR0218588 [/msn]]concerning rational approximation of holomorphic functions and theircontemporary presentation in the language of complex potential theory.The rational approximants \$r\_n(z)\$ have fixed poles \${\textbackslash}\{{\textbackslash}pi\_k{\textbackslash}\}\_\{k=1\}{\textasciicircum}n\$and are supposed to interpolate a function \$f(z)\$, holomorphic in adomain \${\textbackslash}Omega\$ at \$n\$ points \${\textbackslash}\{z\_k{\textbackslash}\}\_\{k=1\}{\textasciicircum}n\$, for definitenesssituated in \$E{\textbackslash}equiv{\textbackslash}vert-1,1{\textbackslash}vert\$. The remarkable conclusion is that,as \$n{\textbackslash}rightarrow{\textbackslash}infty\$, exponential convergence, i.e., \${\textbar}f(z)-r\_n(z){\textbar}=O({\textbackslash}alpha{\textasciicircum}n)\$, \${\textbackslash}alpha\&lt;1\$, \$z{\textbackslash}in{\textbackslash}Omega\$, may be achieved in alarge variety of reciprocal geometries of poles and interpolationpoints. The center of these developments is a celebrated manipulationof the Cauchy integral formula, the Hermite integral, that is, \$\$f(z)-r\_n(z)={\textbackslash}frac\{1\}\{2{\textbackslash}pii\}{\textbackslash}int\_\{{\textbackslash}Gamma\}{\textbackslash}frac\{{\textbackslash}phi(z)\}\{{\textbackslash}phi(t)\}{\textbackslash}frac\{f(t)\}\{t-z\}dt,\$\$where \${\textbackslash}Gamma\$ is a curve contained in \${\textbackslash}Omega\$ enclosing \$E\$ and justavoiding the poles \${\textbackslash}pi\_k\$, leaving them outside (see Figure 12 of the paper).The function \${\textbackslash}phi {\textbackslash}equiv {\textbackslash}Pi\_k(z-z\_k)/(z-{\textbackslash}pi\_k)\$ is obviously smallfor \$z\$ near \$[-1,1]\$ and large near \${\textbackslash}Gamma\$ so that the quantity\${\textbackslash}alpha{\textbackslash}equiv {\textbackslash}sup\_\{t{\textbackslash}in{\textbackslash}Gamma,z{\textbackslash}in E\}{\textbar}{\textbackslash}phi(z)/{\textbackslash}phi(t){\textbar}\$ is a measureof the approximation of the function \$f\$ by \$r\_n\$. Section 6 supports the ideathat the problem of minimizing \${\textbackslash}alpha\$ in the limit of large\$n\$ when poles are distributed on \${\textbackslash}Gamma\$ with density \$d{\textbackslash}mu(t)\$ andinterpolation point fill up \$[-1,1]\$ with density \$d{\textbackslash}mu(z)\$ isequivalent to the problem of finding charge distributions, positive on\${\textbackslash}Gamma\$, negative on \$E\$ minimizing the electrostatic two-dimensionalenergy of the conductors \$E\$ and \${\textbackslash}Gamma\$ with the constraint ofneutrality. The resulting extremal potential functions---solutions ofthe Laplace equation---are constant along the conductors, vanishing on\${\textbackslash}Gamma\$, negative on \$E\$ and allow placing bounds---showingexponential convergence---on the discrepancy \${\textbackslash}vert f(z) - r\_n(z){\textbackslash}vert\$at all points \$z\$ enclosed by \${\textbackslash}Gamma\$ (Theorem 3 of the paper).{\textbackslash}par Section 7 explores the consequences of this result for approximationalong the interval \$E\$ embedded in various geometries, allowing the curve\${\textbackslash}Gamma\$ to consist of several components. The \$(E,{\textbackslash}Gamma)\$ pair is---inanalogy to electrostatics---a ``condenser'', endowed with a capacity\$\{{\textbackslash}rm cap\}(E,{\textbackslash}Gamma)\$, defined as the inverse of the extremal energy value,so that the convergence on the interpolation region \$E\$ is like\${\textbackslash}exp(-1/\{{\textbackslash}rm cap\}(E,{\textbackslash}Gamma))\$. The author shows that rational approximantsmay achieve even superexponential convergence (i.e., \$O({\textbackslash}alpha{\textasciicircum}n)\$ for\${\textbackslash}alpha\$ arbitrarily small) for meromorphic functions or (aspolynomials) for entire functions (Theorem 5).{\textbackslash}par A situation of special interest is that of functions with branchpoints. The curve \${\textbackslash}Gamma\$ may enclose any choice of the cut starting(and ending) at branch points, but the convergence rate depends on thechoice; it turns out (Theorem 6) that an optimal choice exists, whichminimizes \$\{{\textbackslash}rm cap\}(E,{\textbackslash}Gamma)\$. In practice, poles and zeros of the rationalapproximant tend to arrange themselves along curves joining the branchpoints (Figures 17 and 18). A citation of a beautiful theorem of Gonchar andStahl about conditions for accelerated rates of convergence of rationalapproximants closes this section.{\textbackslash}par Section 8, entitled ``Analytic continuation beyond \$E\$'', makes clear thedifference between numerical analytic continuation, which starts fromdata affected with errors, and ``mathematical'' analytic continuation,which inquires about the convergence of, e.g., Padé approximantsobtained from a large finite number of \{{\textbackslash}it exact\} Taylor coefficientsas their number increases indefinitely (Theorem 8 of Nuttall and Pommerenke andTheorem 9 of Stahl). Statements on numerical analyticcontinuation are rather vague, descriptive and contain advice aboutwhat to do if the method of continuation does not produce what oneexpects (e.g., how to remove Froissart doublets).{\textbackslash}par Sections 9 and 10 contain a collection of applications of the AAAalgorithm to the analysis of solutions of several ordinary or partialdifferential equations with the intention to explore the underlyinganalytic structure. An algorithm similar to AAA for continuation in two(complex) dimensions does not appear to exist so far: the examplespresented in Section 10 as attempts at continuations in two realvariables are one-dimensional AAA continuations along families of linesor curves.{\textbackslash}par Upon considering these examples, the skeptical reader---stillunder the impression of the functions displayed in Section 5 (e.g., theinterpolant between \${\textbackslash}sin 20x\$ and (machine)zero, Figure 9)---wonders whythey do not ruin any attempt at analytic continuation (e.g., in Figure 9from the interval \$(1, 2)\$ to the left). These examples actually show thatany sort of analytic continuation from error-affected data on someinterval is bound to be highly ambiguous unless some restrictions areimposed to restore the continuity of the (inverse) linear operatorleading from function values on that interval to the function itself. Ageneral principle adopted in the literature on inverse problems isthat---roughly speaking---the restriction to a compact set in the space offunctions to be reconstructed achieves precisely this. This observation---dueto A.{\textasciitilde}N. Tikhonov [C. R. (Doklady) Acad. Sci. URSS (N.S.) \{{\textbackslash}bf 39\} (1943),176--179; [msn] MR0009685 [/msn]] (see also Chapter I, §2 in [A.{\textasciitilde}N. Tikhonov and V.{\textasciitilde}Y. Arsenin, \{{\textbackslash}it Méthodes de resolution deproblèmes mal posés\}, Mir, Moscow, 1976; [msn] MR0455367 [/msn]])---hasbeen applied, e.g., inanalytic continuation from the interval \$E\$ to the domain \${\textbackslash}Omega\$ in theform of a uniform bound on the sought holomorphic functions (see theinvestigation of the present author on this problem in [BIT \{{\textbackslash}bf 60\}(2020),no.{\textasciitilde}4, 901--915; [msn] MR4179710 [/msn]]). There are other possible choicesof the``stabilizing'' compact set and, correspondingly, several stableextrapolation procedures. In particle physics, this principle wasapplied in the 1960s and 1970s [see S. Ciulli, Nuovo Cimento A (10) \{{\textbackslash}bf 61\} (1969), 787--816; [msn]MR0243781 [/msn]; Nuovo Cimento A (10) \{{\textbackslash}bf 62\} (1969), 301--318;[msn] MR0386517 [/msn]; R.{\textasciitilde}E. Cutkosky, Ann. Physics \{{\textbackslash}bf 54\} (1969),350--378; [msn] MR0250594 [/msn]; S. Ciulli, C. Pomponiu and I.Sabba-Stefanescu, Phys. Reports \{{\textbackslash}bf 17\}(1975), no.{\textasciitilde}4, 133--224, {\textbackslash}doi\{10.1016/0370-1573(75)90006-X\}; G. Nenciu et al.,Nucl. Phys. B \{{\textbackslash}bf 63\} (1973), 285--300,{\textbackslash}doi\{10.1016/0550-3213(73)90147-8\}].In a special geometry, the restoration of continuity of analyticcontinuation can be achieved also for rational functions [I.{\textasciitilde}S. Stefanescu, J. Math. Phys. \{{\textbackslash}bf 21\} (1980), no.{\textasciitilde}1, 175--188; [msn]MR0556288 [/msn]]. Unfortunately, as long as noapplicationof such astabilizing principle (or equivalent) is available to restrict themotion and magnitude of the poles of general rational approximants, oneis compelled to judge their validity only according to vagueexpectations or preferences.{\textbackslash}par To conclude, this survey is an excellent primer in approximationtheory, but can also leave the reader in a confused stateconcerning the reliability of numerical analytic continuation byunrestricted rational functions.},
	language = {eng},
